<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en-CA">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">

  <meta
    name="viewport"
    content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"
  >

  <title>Calgary Wildlife Help | Local Wildlife Information</title>

  <meta
    name="description"
    content="Calgary wildlife information about raccoons, squirrels, bats, skunks, birds, animals in attics, prevention, costs, and connections to independent local providers."
  >

  <meta
    name="robots"
    content="index, follow, max-image-preview:large"
  >

  <link
    rel="canonical"
    href="https://calgarywildlifehelp.com/"
  >

  <meta
    name="theme-color"
    content="#174a35"
  >

  <meta
    property="og:type"
    content="website"
  >

  <meta
    property="og:title"
    content="Calgary Wildlife Help"
  >

  <meta
    property="og:description"
    content="Clear local wildlife information and connections to independent Calgary-area providers."
  >

  <meta
    property="og:url"
    content="https://calgarywildlifehelp.com/"
  >

  <meta
    property="og:site_name"
    content="Calgary Wildlife Help"
  >

  <meta
    name="twitter:card"
    content="summary"
  >

  <style>
    :root {
      --ink: #173126;
      --muted: #52645c;
      --brand: #236b4b;
      --brand-dark: #174a35;
      --soft: #edf6f0;
      --line: #d7e4dc;
      --paper: #ffffff;
      --accent: #f4b942;
      --danger: #8b2e2e;
      --max: 1120px;
      --radius: 16px;
      --shadow: 0 10px 30px rgba(22, 58, 42, 0.08);
    }

    * {
      box-sizing: border-box;
    }

    html {
      scroll-behavior: smooth;
    }

    body {
      margin: 0;
      font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
      color: var(--ink);
      background: #fbfdfb;
      line-height: 1.65;
    }

    a {
      color: var(--brand-dark);
    }

    a:hover {
      text-decoration-thickness: 2px;
    }

    img {
      max-width: 100%;
      height: auto;
    }

    .container {
      width: min(calc(100% - 32px), var(--max));
      margin: 0 auto;
    }

    .skip-link {
      position: absolute;
      left: -999px;
      top: 8px;
      z-index: 100;
      background: #ffffff;
      color: var(--ink);
      padding: 10px 14px;
      border-radius: 8px;
    }

    .skip-link:focus {
      left: 8px;
    }

    .site-header {
      position: sticky;
      top: 0;
      z-index: 50;
      background: #ffffff;
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line);
    }

    .header-inner {
      min-height: 74px;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: space-between;
      gap: 24px;
    }

    .brand {
      color: var(--ink);
      text-decoration: none;
      font-weight: 800;
      font-size: 1.08rem;
    }

    .nav {
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 18px;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
    }

    .nav a {
      color: var(--ink);
      text-decoration: none;
      font-weight: 700;
      font-size: 0.93rem;
    }

    .nav a:hover {
      color: var(--brand);
    }

    .phone-button,
    .primary-button {
      display: inline-block;
      background: var(--brand);
      color: #ffffff !important;
      text-decoration: none;
      padding: 12px 18px;
      border-radius: 999px;
      font-weight: 800;
      border: 0;
      cursor: pointer;
    }

    .phone-button:hover,
    .primary-button:hover {
      background: var(--brand-dark);
    }

    .secondary-button {
      display: inline-block;
      border: 2px solid var(--brand);
      background: #ffffff;
      color: var(--brand-dark);
      text-decoration: none;
      padding: 10px 17px;
      border-radius: 999px;
      font-weight: 800;
    }

    .hero {
      padding: 76px 0 58px;
      background:
        linear-gradient(
          135deg,
          #e8f5ec 0%,
          #ffffff 72%
        );
    }

    .eyebrow {
      margin-bottom: 12px;
      color: var(--brand);
      font-size: 0.8rem;
      font-weight: 800;
      letter-spacing: 0.12em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
    }

    h1,
    h2,
    h3 {
      line-height: 1.2;
      margin-top: 0;
    }

    h1 {
      max-width: 900px;
      margin-bottom: 18px;
      font-size: clamp(2.25rem, 5vw, 4.5rem);
    }

    h2 {
      margin-bottom: 18px;
      font-size: clamp(1.6rem, 3vw, 2.4rem);
    }

    h3 {
      font-size: 1.2rem;
    }

    .lead {
      max-width: 780px;
      color: var(--muted);
      font-size: 1.18rem;
    }

    .actions {
      display: flex;
      gap: 12px;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      margin-top: 28px;
    }

    .trust-note {
      margin-top: 14px;
      color: var(--muted);
      font-size: 0.92rem;
    }

    .section {
      padding: 64px 0;
    }

    .section.alt {
      background: var(--soft);
    }

    .section-heading {
      max-width: 760px;
      margin-bottom: 34px;
    }

    .section-heading p {
      color: var(--muted);
    }

    .grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
      gap: 20px;
    }

    .card {
      padding: 24px;
      background: var(--paper);
      border: 1px solid var(--line);
      border-radius: var(--radius);
      box-shadow: var(--shadow);
    }

    .card p {
      color: var(--muted);
    }

    .card a {
      font-weight: 800;
    }

    .two-col {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 1.45fr 0.75fr;
      gap: 36px;
      align-items: start;
    }

    .content {
      max-width: 820px;
    }

    .content h2 {
      margin-top: 42px;
    }

    .content h3 {
      margin-top: 30px;
    }

    .content li {
      margin-bottom: 8px;
    }

    aside {
      padding: 22px;
      background: var(--soft);
      border: 1px solid var(--line);
      border-radius: var(--radius);
    }

    .notice {
      padding: 18px 20px;
      background: #fff9e8;
      border-left: 5px solid var(--accent);
      border-radius: 8px;
    }

    .danger-notice {
      padding: 18px 20px;
      background: #fff2f2;
      border-left: 5px solid var(--danger);
      border-radius: 8px;
    }

    .service-section {
      scroll-margin-top: 100px;
    }

    .badge {
      display: inline-block;
      margin: 3px;
      padding: 6px 10px;
      background: var(--soft);
      border: 1px solid var(--line);
      border-radius: 999px;
      font-size: 0.82rem;
      font-weight: 800;
    }

    .faq details {
      margin: 12px 0;
      padding: 16px 18px;
      background: #ffffff;
      border: 1px solid var(--line);
      border-radius: 12px;
    }

    .faq summary {
      cursor: pointer;
      font-weight: 800;
    }

    .cta {
      padding: 36px;
      color: #ffffff;
      background: var(--brand-dark);
      border-radius: var(--radius);
    }

    .cta p {
      color: #e3f2e9;
    }

    .cta .secondary-button {
      color: var(--brand-dark);
    }

    .form {
      display: grid;
      gap: 15px;
    }

    label {
      font-weight: 800;
    }

    input,
    textarea,
    select {
      width: 100%;
      padding: 13px;
      font: inherit;
      background: #ffffff;
      border: 1px solid #aebfb5;
      border-radius: 10px;
    }

    textarea {
      min-height: 150px;
      resize: vertical;
    }

    button {
      font: inherit;
    }

    .small {
      color: var(--muted);
      font-size: 0.9rem;
    }

    .divider {
      margin: 40px 0;
      border: 0;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
    }

    .legal {
      max-width: 850px;
    }

    .legal h2 {
      margin-top: 36px;
      font-size: 1.5rem;
    }

    .site-footer {
      margin-top: 60px;
      padding: 48px 0 28px;
      color: #dbe9e1;
      background: #10251b;
    }

    .footer-grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 2fr 1fr 1fr;
      gap: 28px;
    }

    .site-footer a {
      color: #ffffff;
    }

    .disclaimer {
      margin-top: 28px;
      padding-top: 22px;
      color: #bcd0c4;
      border-top: 1px solid #345145;
      font-size: 0.84rem;
    }

    @media (max-width: 850px) {
      .site-header {
        position: static;
      }

      .header-inner {
        flex-direction: column;
        align-items: flex-start;
        padding: 14px 0;
      }

      .nav {
        gap: 12px;
      }

      .grid,
      .two-col,
      .footer-grid {
        grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      }

      .hero {
        padding-top: 48px;
      }

      .phone-button {
        width: 100%;
        text-align: center;
      }
    }
  </style>

  <script type="application/ld+json">
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "Calgary Wildlife Help",
    "url": "https://calgarywildlifehelp.com/",
    "description": "An independent educational resource that helps Calgary-area property owners learn about common wildlife issues and connect with independent service providers.",
    "areaServed": {
      "@type": "City",
      "name": "Calgary"
    }
  }
  </script>

  <script type="application/ld+json">
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebSite",
    "name": "Calgary Wildlife Help",
    "url": "https://calgarywildlifehelp.com/",
    "inLanguage": "en-CA"
  }
  </script>

  <script type="application/ld+json">
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What should I do if I hear an animal in my attic?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Keep people and pets away, avoid sealing the entry point, and contact a qualified wildlife provider who can identify the animal and determine whether dependent young are present."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much does wildlife removal cost in Calgary?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Pricing depends on the species, access, number of entry points, presence of young animals, repairs, cleanup, equipment, and follow-up. Request a written estimate from the independent provider."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does Calgary Wildlife Help perform wildlife removal?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. Calgary Wildlife Help provides general educational information and may connect visitors with independent third-party wildlife providers."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Should I seal an animal entry hole immediately?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. Sealing an opening before all animals and dependent young are safely out can trap wildlife inside the building."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
  </script>
</head>

<body>
  <a class="skip-link" href="#main">
    Skip to content
  </a>

  <header class="site-header">
    <div class="container header-inner">
      <a class="brand" href="#top">
        Calgary Wildlife Help
      </a>

      <nav class="nav" aria-label="Main navigation">
        <a href="#services">Services</a>
        <a href="#learning-centre">Learning Centre</a>
        <a href="#cost-guide">Cost Guide</a>
        <a href="#contact">Contact</a>
        <a href="#privacy">Privacy</a>

        <a
          class="phone-button"
          href="tel:+15870000000"
        >
          (587) 000-0000
        </a>
      </nav>
    </div>
  </header>

  <main id="main">

    <section class="hero" id="top">
      <div class="container">
        <p class="eyebrow">
          Independent Calgary wildlife information
        </p>

        <h1>
          Understand your wildlife problem before choosing a provider
        </h1>

        <p class="lead">
          Clear information about raccoons, squirrels, bats,
          skunks, birds, animals in attics, warning signs,
          prevention, costs, and questions to ask an independent
          Calgary wildlife professional.
        </p>

        <div class="actions">
          <a
            class="primary-button"
            href="tel:+15870000000"
          >
            Call (587) 000-0000
          </a>

          <a
            class="secondary-button"
            href="#contact"
          >
            Request a callback
          </a>
        </div>

        <p class="trust-note">
          Calgary Wildlife Help does not perform wildlife-control
          work. Requests may be shared with independent local providers.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="services">
      <div class="container">

        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">
            Wildlife topics
          </p>

          <h2>
            Start with the problem you noticed
          </h2>

          <p>
            Use these guides to understand common warning signs
            before speaking with a local provider.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid">

          <article class="card">
            <h3>
              Animal in the attic
            </h3>

            <p>
              Scratching, movement, droppings, odors, or damaged
              vents may point to an animal using the attic.
            </p>

            <a href="#animal-in-attic">
              Read the attic guide
            </a>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>
              Raccoon activity
            </h3>

            <p>
              Learn about nighttime noise, roof damage, denning,
              droppings, and why young animals affect the plan.
            </p>

            <a href="#raccoons">
              Read the raccoon guide
            </a>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>
              Bat activity
            </h3>

            <p>
              Learn why timing, species protection, and possible
              human or pet contact require special care.
            </p>

            <a href="#bats">
              Read the bat guide
            </a>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>
              Squirrel activity
            </h3>

            <p>
              Review roofline entry points, daytime sounds,
              chewing concerns, and prevention methods.
            </p>

            <a href="#squirrels">
              Read the squirrel guide
            </a>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>
              Skunks under a structure
            </h3>

            <p>
              Understand burrows, odor, pets, denning, and safer
              next steps for a skunk beneath a deck or shed.
            </p>

            <a href="#skunks">
              Read the skunk guide
            </a>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>
              Birds in vents or chimneys
            </h3>

            <p>
              Learn about nesting material, blocked airflow,
              active nests, and lawful exclusion.
            </p>

            <a href="#birds">
              Read the bird guide
            </a>
          </article>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section alt">
      <div class="container two-col">

        <article class="content">
          <h2>
            How this website works
          </h2>

          <ol>
            <li>
              Read the guide that matches the problem you noticed.
            </li>

            <li>
              Call or use the contact form.
            </li>

            <li>
              Your request may be shared with an independent provider
              serving Calgary.
            </li>

            <li>
              The provider explains its own availability, inspection
              process, methods, pricing, warranties, and terms.
            </li>
          </ol>

          <div class="notice">
            <strong>No fixed-price promises:</strong>
            We do not publish exact prices because every property,
            animal, access point, repair, and cleanup requirement
            is different. Ask the provider for a written scope and estimate.
          </div>
        </article>

        <aside>
          <h2>
            Questions to ask a provider
          </h2>

          <ul>
            <li>
              How will the animal be identified?
            </li>

            <li>
              Are young animals likely to be present?
            </li>

            <li>
              What removal or exclusion method will be used?
            </li>

            <li>
              What repairs are included?
            </li>

            <li>
              Is cleanup included?
            </li>

            <li>
              Is follow-up included?
            </li>

            <li>
              What written warranty applies?
            </li>
          </ul>
        </aside>

      </div>
    </section>

    <section
      class="section service-section"
      id="animal-in-attic"
    >
      <div class="container two-col">

        <article class="content">
          <p class="eyebrow">
            Calgary attic wildlife
          </p>

          <h2>
            Animal in the attic
          </h2>

          <p>
            Scratching, movement, odors, droppings, or damage near
            vents and soffits can indicate wildlife activity in an attic.
          </p>

          <h3>
            Clues that help identify the animal
          </h3>

          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Time of day:</strong>
              Daytime movement may suggest squirrels or birds.
              Heavy nighttime movement may suggest raccoons.
            </li>

            <li>
              <strong>Sound:</strong>
              Fluttering, chirping, chewing, scratching, or heavy
              thumping may point to different animals.
            </li>

            <li>
              <strong>Entry damage:</strong>
              Damaged soffits, vents, fascia, chimneys, or roof
              edges may reveal the access point.
            </li>

            <li>
              <strong>Droppings:</strong>
              Do not touch them. Their appearance and location may
              help a trained provider identify the species.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3>
            What not to do
          </h3>

          <p>
            Do not enter a confined attic without suitable training
            and protective equipment. Do not seal an opening until
            all animals and dependent young are confirmed out.
          </p>
        </article>

        <aside>
          <h3>
            Common attic animals
          </h3>

          <span class="badge">Raccoons</span>
          <span class="badge">Squirrels</span>
          <span class="badge">Bats</span>
          <span class="badge">Birds</span>
          <span class="badge">Mice</span>
          <span class="badge">Rats</span>
        </aside>

      </div>
    </section>

    <section
      class="section alt service-section"
      id="raccoons"
    >
      <div class="container two-col">

        <article class="content">
          <p class="eyebrow">
            Raccoon information
          </p>

          <h2>
            Raccoon activity in Calgary homes
          </h2>

          <p>
            Raccoons may use attics, chimneys, roof openings, and
            sheltered areas as denning locations.
          </p>

          <h3>
            Common signs
          </h3>

          <ul>
            <li>
              Heavy movement or thumping at night
            </li>

            <li>
              Damage around roof vents, soffits, or chimneys
            </li>

            <li>
              Large droppings or a strong attic odor
            </li>

            <li>
              Disturbed or compressed insulation
            </li>

            <li>
              Repeated travel along the roof or fence
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3>
            Why young raccoons matter
          </h3>

          <p>
            A mother may be sheltering with dependent young.
            A provider should check for this before exclusion or
            sealing. Removing an adult without accounting for young
            can create animal-welfare, odor, and property-damage problems.
          </p>

          <h3>
            Questions to ask
          </h3>

          <ul>
            <li>
              How will you confirm whether young are present?
            </li>

            <li>
              What active and vulnerable entry points will be repaired?
            </li>

            <li>
              Is contamination cleanup quoted separately?
            </li>

            <li>
              What follow-up and warranty are included?
            </li>
          </ul>
        </article>

        <aside>
          <h3>
            Safety reminder
          </h3>

          <p>
            Raccoons are wild animals and should not be touched,
            fed, cornered, or handled.
          </p>

          <p>
            Keep children and pets away.
          </p>

          <p>
            For a bite, scratch, or suspected rabies exposure,
            seek prompt medical or public-health guidance.
          </p>
        </aside>

      </div>
    </section>

    <section
      class="section service-section"
      id="squirrels"
    >
      <div class="container two-col">

        <article class="content">
          <p class="eyebrow">
            Squirrel information
          </p>

          <h2>
            Squirrels in attics and roof spaces
          </h2>

          <p>
            Squirrels commonly enter buildings through damaged
            soffits, vents, fascia, and gaps near roof edges.
          </p>

          <h3>
            Common signs
          </h3>

          <ul>
            <li>
              Fast scratching or scampering during daylight
            </li>

            <li>
              Chewing sounds in an attic or wall
            </li>

            <li>
              Damage near soffits, vents, or roof edges
            </li>

            <li>
              Nesting material in an attic
            </li>

            <li>
              Frequent squirrel activity along the roofline
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3>
            Why chewing matters
          </h3>

          <p>
            Squirrels may chew wood, stored items, vents, and wiring.
            Avoid touching damaged wiring. Ask whether an electrician
            or another qualified trade should inspect it.
          </p>

          <h3>
            Long-term prevention
          </h3>

          <p>
            Removal should be followed by secure repair of entry points.
            Weak vent covers and nearby branches may also need attention.
          </p>
        </article>

        <aside>
          <h3>
            Important
          </h3>

          <p>
            Do not block a suspected squirrel opening until a provider
            confirms that the adult animals and dependent young are out.
          </p>
        </aside>

      </div>
    </section>

    <section
      class="section alt service-section"
      id="bats"
    >
      <div class="container two-col">

        <article class="content">
          <p class="eyebrow">
            Bat information
          </p>

          <h2>
            Bats in Calgary buildings
          </h2>

          <p>
            Bats can use narrow openings around rooflines, vents,
            soffits, walls, and chimneys.
          </p>

          <h3>
            Possible signs
          </h3>

          <ul>
            <li>
              Bats leaving a roofline around dusk
            </li>

            <li>
              Small droppings below a recurring opening
            </li>

            <li>
              Light chirping or movement inside a wall or attic
            </li>

            <li>
              Staining around a narrow entry gap
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3>
            Do not handle a bat
          </h3>

          <p>
            Keep people and pets away. A bat found in a living area,
            especially where direct contact cannot be ruled out,
            may require guidance from public-health or animal-control
            authorities.
          </p>

          <h3>
            Why timing matters
          </h3>

          <p>
            Bats and maternity colonies may be legally protected.
            Exclusion may be restricted during sensitive periods.
            A knowledgeable provider should follow current Alberta
            requirements and species-protection guidance.
          </p>

          <p>
            Official resource:
            <a
              href="https://www.alberta.ca/bat-management"
              rel="noopener"
            >
              Alberta bat management guidance
            </a>.
          </p>
        </article>

        <aside>
          <div class="danger-notice">
            <strong>Possible exposure:</strong>
            If a bat was found in a room with a sleeping person,
            child, impaired person, or pet, contact the appropriate
            health or animal authority before releasing it.
          </div>
        </aside>

      </div>
    </section>

    <section
      class="section service-section"
      id="skunks"
    >
      <div class="container two-col">

        <article class="content">
          <p class="eyebrow">
            Skunk information
          </p>

          <h2>
            Skunks under decks, sheds, and porches
          </h2>

          <p>
            Protected spaces beneath decks, sheds, steps, and porches
            may be used as temporary or seasonal dens.
          </p>

          <h3>
            Common signs
          </h3>

          <ul>
            <li>
              Persistent skunk odor
            </li>

            <li>
              A burrow beneath a deck, porch, shed, or step
            </li>

            <li>
              Digging in lawn areas
            </li>

            <li>
              Nighttime sightings
            </li>

            <li>
              A pet repeatedly focusing on one location
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3>
            Do not block a den without checking it
          </h3>

          <p>
            A den may contain dependent young. Closing the entrance
            too early can trap animals and create welfare and odor problems.
          </p>

          <h3>
            After the animals leave
          </h3>

          <p>
            A provider may recommend confirming vacancy, securing
            the opening, and adding a buried barrier where appropriate.
          </p>

          <p>
            Official resource:
            <a
              href="https://www.alberta.ca/skunks"
              rel="noopener"
            >
              Alberta skunk guidance
            </a>.
          </p>
        </article>

        <aside>
          <h3>
            Reduce the chance of spraying
          </h3>

          <ul>
            <li>
              Keep your distance
            </li>

            <li>
              Move slowly
            </li>

            <li>
              Bring pets indoors
            </li>

            <li>
              Do not corner the animal
            </li>

            <li>
              Avoid loud or sudden movements
            </li>
          </ul>
        </aside>

      </div>
    </section>

    <section
      class="section alt service-section"
      id="birds"
    >
      <div class="container two-col">

        <article class="content">
          <p class="eyebrow">
            Bird information
          </p>

          <h2>
            Birds in vents, chimneys, and roof spaces
          </h2>

          <p>
            Birds may nest inside vents, chimneys, roof voids,
            soffits, and other sheltered openings.
          </p>

          <h3>
            Common warning signs
          </h3>

          <ul>
            <li>
              Chirping from a vent, chimney, or roof space
            </li>

            <li>
              Nesting material at an opening
            </li>

            <li>
              Droppings below a vent
            </li>

            <li>
              Reduced airflow from an exhaust vent
            </li>

            <li>
              Adult birds repeatedly entering the same location
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3>
            Why identification matters
          </h3>

          <p>
            Different bird species and active nests may be legally
            protected. A provider should identify the situation
            and use lawful methods.
          </p>

          <h3>
            Preventing repeat nesting
          </h3>

          <p>
            After lawful removal and once the opening is confirmed
            empty, damaged covers may be replaced with suitable
            wildlife-resistant vent protection.
          </p>

          <p>
            Official resource:
            <a
              href="https://www.canada.ca/en/environment-climate-change/services/avoiding-harm-migratory-birds/reduce-risk-migratory-birds.html"
              rel="noopener"
            >
              Government of Canada migratory bird guidance
            </a>.
          </p>
        </article>

        <aside>
          <h3>
            Blocked vents can matter
          </h3>

          <p>
            A blocked exhaust vent may reduce airflow and create
            moisture, appliance, or fire concerns depending on
            the vent type.
          </p>
        </aside>

      </div>
    </section>

    <section
      class="section service-section"
      id="dead-animal"
    >
      <div class="container two-col">

        <article class="content">
          <p class="eyebrow">
            Odor and removal information
          </p>

          <h2>
            Dead animal inside a wall, attic, or crawl space
          </h2>

          <h3>
            Common signs
          </h3>

          <ul>
            <li>
              A strong odor concentrated in one area
            </li>

            <li>
              Increased fly or insect activity
            </li>

            <li>
              A ceiling or wall stain
            </li>

            <li>
              Recent animal noises that suddenly stopped
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3>
            Why locating the source matters
          </h3>

          <p>
            Opening walls or ceilings without a plan may cause
            unnecessary damage. A provider may use the odor pattern,
            building layout, and inspection tools to narrow the location.
          </p>

          <h3>
            Cleanup considerations
          </h3>

          <p>
            The scope may include removal, disposal, surface cleaning,
            odor treatment, and repair. Ask which items are included
            in the written estimate.
          </p>
        </article>

        <aside>
          <h3>
            Other trades may be needed
          </h3>

          <p>
            Depending on the location, a roofer, carpenter,
            electrician, insulation contractor, or restoration
            provider may also be required.
          </p>
        </aside>

      </div>
    </section>

    <section
      class="section alt"
      id="learning-centre"
    >
      <div class="container">

        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">
            Learning centre
          </p>

          <h2>
            Common Calgary wildlife questions
          </h2>

          <p>
            Short answers designed to help homeowners understand
            the next safe step.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid">

          <article class="card">
            <h3>
              Why am I hearing scratching in my ceiling?
            </h3>

            <p>
              Time of day and sound type can help narrow the
              likely animal.
            </p>

            <p>
              Daytime activity may suggest squirrels or birds.
              Heavy nighttime movement may suggest raccoons.
              Light scratching can have several possible causes.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>
              What animals commonly enter attics?
            </h3>

            <p>
              Raccoons, squirrels, bats, birds, mice, and rats
              may use attics and roof spaces.
            </p>

            <p>
              Correct identification matters because the method,
              timing, and provider may differ.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>
              When are bats active in Alberta?
            </h3>

            <p>
              Bat activity is generally easier to notice during
              warmer months.
            </p>

            <p>
              Exclusion timing depends on species, weather,
              occupancy, maternity periods, and current rules.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>
              Do raccoons carry diseases?
            </h3>

            <p>
              Raccoons can carry pathogens and parasites.
              Avoid direct contact and do not handle droppings
              without suitable training and protection.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>
              How can I help keep squirrels out?
            </h3>

            <p>
              Maintain roofline materials, protect vents,
              manage nearby branches, and repair gaps after
              the attic is confirmed empty.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>
              Should I seal the hole myself?
            </h3>

            <p>
              Only after all animals and dependent young are
              confirmed out and the repair will not block required
              ventilation or drainage.
            </p>
          </article>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section
      class="section"
      id="cost-guide"
    >
      <div class="container two-col">

        <article class="content">
          <p class="eyebrow">
            Pricing information
          </p>

          <h2>
            Wildlife-removal cost factors in Calgary
          </h2>

          <p>
            There is no single reliable online price because a
            simple exterior exclusion and a complex attic den are
            not the same job.
          </p>

          <h3>
            Common quote factors
          </h3>

          <ul>
            <li>
              Inspection and species identification
            </li>

            <li>
              Building height and access difficulty
            </li>

            <li>
              Number and size of entry points
            </li>

            <li>
              Removal or exclusion method
            </li>

            <li>
              Presence of dependent young
            </li>

            <li>
              Vent, soffit, chimney, fascia, or roof repairs
            </li>

            <li>
              Cleanup or insulation work
            </li>

            <li>
              Return visits and warranty
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3>
            How to compare providers
          </h3>

          <p>
            Ask for a written scope. Compare what is included,
            not only the total price. Confirm whether repair materials,
            follow-up, cleanup, taxes, and warranty are included.
          </p>

          <div class="notice">
            <strong>This website does not set prices.</strong>
            Independent providers determine their own charges,
            estimates, scope, and service terms.
          </div>
        </article>

        <aside>
          <h3>
            Ask for these items in writing
          </h3>

          <ul>
            <li>
              Inspection fee
            </li>

            <li>
              Removal method
            </li>

            <li>
              Number of openings repaired
            </li>

            <li>
              Materials used
            </li>

            <li>
              Cleanup included
            </li>

            <li>
              Follow-up visits
            </li>

            <li>
              Warranty length
            </li>

            <li>
              Taxes and additional charges
            </li>
          </ul>
        </aside>

      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section alt">
      <div class="container two-col">

        <article class="content">
          <p class="eyebrow">
            Insurance questions
          </p>

          <h2>
            Does home insurance cover wildlife damage?
          </h2>

          <p>
            Coverage depends on the policy, cause of loss,
            maintenance history, exclusions, and type of damage.
          </p>

          <p>
            Some policies may treat sudden damage differently
            from infestation, gradual damage, cleanup, or
            preventative repairs.
          </p>

          <h3>
            Document the situation
          </h3>

          <ul>
            <li>
              Take safe photographs from accessible areas
            </li>

            <li>
              Keep inspection reports and written estimates
            </li>

            <li>
              Record when the problem was first noticed
            </li>

            <li>
              Ask the insurer before authorizing non-urgent demolition
            </li>
          </ul>

          <p>
            The insurer—not this website or the wildlife provider—
            determines coverage.
          </p>
        </article>

        <aside>
          <h3>
            Ask your insurer
          </h3>

          <ul>
            <li>
              What deductible applies?
            </li>

            <li>
              What exclusions apply?
            </li>

            <li>
              Is pre-approval required?
            </li>

            <li>
              What documents are needed?
            </li>

            <li>
              Is emergency mitigation covered?
            </li>
          </ul>
        </aside>

      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section faq">
      <div class="container content">

        <p class="eyebrow">
          Frequently asked questions
        </p>

        <h2>
          Quick answers
        </h2>

        <details>
          <summary>
            Does Calgary Wildlife Help perform wildlife removal?
          </summary>

          <p>
            No. Calgary Wildlife Help provides general educational
            information and may connect visitors with independent
            third-party providers.
          </p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>
            Is wildlife removal an emergency?
          </summary>

          <p>
            Most attic and exterior wildlife issues are urgent but
            are not medical emergencies. For a bite, scratch,
            suspected rabies exposure, direct bat contact, or immediate
            danger, contact the appropriate medical, public-health,
            animal-control, or emergency authority.
          </p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>
            Can a provider give a price over the phone?
          </summary>

          <p>
            A provider may explain general factors, but a dependable
            scope often requires an inspection of the animal activity,
            entry points, building access, and damage.
          </p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>
            Should I use poison?
          </summary>

          <p>
            Poison can create animal-welfare, legal, odor,
            secondary-exposure, and property-damage risks.
            Ask a qualified provider about lawful and humane options.
          </p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>
            Will sealing one opening solve the problem?
          </summary>

          <p>
            Only if all active and vulnerable entry points are assessed,
            no animals are trapped inside, and the repair uses materials
            appropriate for the building component.
          </p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>
            How long does wildlife removal take?
          </summary>

          <p>
            The timeline depends on the species, season, weather,
            building access, dependent young, repairs, monitoring,
            and follow-up requirements.
          </p>
        </details>

      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="contact">
      <div class="container">

        <div class="cta">
          <h2>
            Describe the wildlife problem
          </h2>

          <p>
            Call or leave your information below. Your request may
            be shared with an independent local provider who can
            discuss availability, inspection, pricing, and next steps.
          </p>

          <div class="actions">
            <a
              class="primary-button"
              href="tel:+15870000000"
            >
              Call (587) 000-0000
            </a>

            <a
              class="secondary-button"
              href="mailto:hello@calgarywildlifehelp.com"
            >
              Email Calgary Wildlife Help
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="two-col" style="margin-top: 40px;">

          <article class="content">
            <h2>
              Request a callback
            </h2>

            <p>
              This form opens your email application. A dedicated
              website form service can be connected later.
            </p>

            <form
              class="form"
              action="mailto:hello@calgarywildlifehelp.com"
              method="post"
              enctype="text/plain"
            >

              <label for="name">
                Name
              </label>

              <input
                id="name"
                name="Name"
                type="text"
                autocomplete="name"
                required
              >

              <label for="phone">
                Phone number
              </label>

              <input
                id="phone"
                name="Phone"
                type="tel"
                autocomplete="tel"
                required
              >

              <label for="email">
                Email address
              </label>

              <input
                id="email"
                name="Email"
                type="email"
                autocomplete="email"
              >

              <label for="area">
                Calgary neighbourhood or nearby community
              </label>

              <input
                id="area"
                name="Area"
                type="text"
              >

              <label for="issue">
                What are you hearing or seeing?
              </label>

              <textarea
                id="issue"
                name="Wildlife issue"
                required
              ></textarea>

              <label>
                <input
                  style="width: auto;"
                  type="checkbox"
                  name="Consent"
                  value="Yes"
                  required
                >

                I understand that my request may be shared with
                an independent local provider.
              </label>

              <button
                class="primary-button"
                type="submit"
              >
                Prepare email request
              </button>
            </form>
          </article>

          <aside>
            <div class="danger-notice">
              <strong>Do not use this form for emergencies.</strong>

              <p>
                For a bite, scratch, suspected rabies exposure,
                direct bat contact, immediate danger, or a medical
                emergency, contact the appropriate public authority
                or emergency service.
              </p>
            </div>
          </aside>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section alt" id="privacy">
      <div class="container legal">

        <p class="eyebrow">
          Privacy
        </p>

        <h2>
          Privacy Policy
        </h2>

        <p>
          Effective date: June 17, 2026
        </p>

        <h2>
          Information we may collect
        </h2>

        <p>
          When you call, email, or submit information, Calgary Wildlife
          Help may receive your name, phone number, email address,
          general location, description of the wildlife issue, call
          metadata, and other information you choose to provide.
        </p>

        <h2>
          How information may be used
        </h2>

        <p>
          Information may be used to respond to your request,
          operate and improve the website, prevent abuse, measure
          lead quality, and connect you with an independent provider.
        </p>

        <p>
          Your request may be shared with one or more independent
          providers that may serve your area.
        </p>

        <h2>
          Call tracking
        </h2>

        <p>
          Calls to a tracking number may be logged or recorded where
          lawful. Any legally required notice or consent should be
          configured with the phone provider before recording calls.
        </p>

        <h2>
          Cookies and analytics
        </h2>

        <p>
          This version of the website does not require advertising
          cookies. Privacy-conscious analytics may be added later.
          Additional disclosure and consent may be required before
          enabling advertising, retargeting, or non-essential tracking.
        </p>

        <h2>
          Retention and security
        </h2>

        <p>
          Personal information should be kept only as long as reasonably
          needed for the stated purpose, legal obligations, dispute
          resolution, and abuse prevention. No storage method is
          completely secure.
        </p>

        <h2>
          Your choices
        </h2>

        <p>
          You may ask about, correct, or request deletion of personal
          information, subject to applicable legal and operational
          requirements, by emailing:
        </p>

        <p>
          <a href="mailto:hello@calgarywildlifehelp.com">
            hello@calgarywildlifehelp.com
          </a>
        </p>

        <h2>
          Children
        </h2>

        <p>
          This website is not directed to children.
        </p>

        <div class="notice">
          <strong>Legal review recommended:</strong>
          This privacy wording is a general template and is not legal
          advice. Obtain appropriate legal review before collecting,
          recording, sharing, or selling leads.
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="terms">
      <div class="container legal">

        <p class="eyebrow">
          Terms
        </p>

        <h2>
          Terms of Use
        </h2>

        <p>
          Effective date: June 17, 2026
        </p>

        <h2>
          Educational and referral role
        </h2>

        <p>
          Calgary Wildlife Help provides general information and may
          connect visitors with independent third-party providers.
          Calgary Wildlife Help does not perform, supervise, guarantee,
          or warrant provider services.
        </p>

        <h2>
          No professional advice
        </h2>

        <p>
          Website information is general and may not fit your property,
          animal, health, legal, insurance, or safety situation.
          Seek qualified advice when needed.
        </p>

        <h2>
          Independent providers
        </h2>

        <p>
          Providers are responsible for their licensing, insurance,
          methods, pricing, estimates, contracts, taxes, warranties,
          workmanship, safety, and legal compliance.
        </p>

        <p>
          Visitors should independently verify a provider before hiring.
        </p>

        <h2>
          No guaranteed availability or result
        </h2>

        <p>
          Calling or submitting a request does not guarantee a response,
          appointment, price, outcome, service area, or completed service.
        </p>

        <h2>
          Emergency limitation
        </h2>

        <p>
          Do not rely on this website for emergencies. Contact the
          appropriate emergency, medical, health, animal-control,
          or public authority.
        </p>

        <h2>
          Acceptable use
        </h2>

        <p>
          Do not submit false information, interfere with the website,
          scrape personal information, attempt unauthorized access,
          or use the website unlawfully.
        </p>

        <h2>
          Liability
        </h2>

        <p>
          To the extent permitted by law, the website owner is not
          responsible for losses arising from reliance on general
          information, third-party services, provider conduct,
          service delays, or website interruption.
        </p>

        <div class="notice">
          <strong>Legal review recommended:</strong>
          These terms are a general template and are not legal advice.
          Obtain legal review for your ownership structure, jurisdiction,
          call recording, privacy obligations, and lead-sharing practices.
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

